contributingFactors: No evidence connecting motive with allegation.

data.rationale: A reticent demeanor is common even when making true allegation due to trauma, shame, embarrassment...etc. This lowers the weight of the evidence.
It's common for victims of SA to provide contrary statements prior to outcry until they've decided to do so. This lowers the weight of this evidence.
The second encounter was initiated by the Respondent. While she overtly consented, she did so passively and her explanation for why she did so is plausible.
While laughing indicates she wasn't actively 'fighting,' it's more significant that she was physically resisting.

The Complainant clearly expressed, through body language, that she didn't wish to go into the closet. There are alternative explanations for why she laughed. The evidence supports the narrative that the encounter was non-consensual, but the Complainant didn't wish to anger or upset the Respondent by objecting more forcefully.
Attorney for accused asserted that the jump suit would have made assault as described physically impossible, but this is not supported by evidence.
